<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 94 / Finance and the Family: Making the most - Annuities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER QUINTON, Annuity Bureau
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If a couple retires, each spouse having accumulated their own pension funds,
the question always arises: should they buy a single or joint life annuity?
Take a couple with Pounds 100,000 each in their pension funds.
If the husband, aged 65, uses his Pounds 100,000 and buys a joint life
annuity from Canada Life (see table), his gross annual annuity will be
Pounds 9,234.48.
If the wife, aged 63, uses her Pounds 100,000 to do likewise, hers will be
Pounds 9,162.96.
Should both buy single annuities with the same benefits, however, the
husband would receive a gross annual income of Pounds 11,643.12 and the wife
Pounds 9,951.48.
So, the total gross annual income for the couple with a joint life scheme
would be Pounds 18,397.44. And should one die before the other, the income
would remain at this level until the survivor's death.
But if, on the other hand, each bought a single life annuity, they would get
an initial gross income of Pounds 21,594.60.
Of course, the death of either partner would mean their portion of the
income died with them. This means that if the husband died first, for
example, she would be left with an income of Pounds 9,951.48 for the rest of
her life.
Even when there is a big difference between spouse's fund values, couples
normally choose a combination of single and joint life annuities, with a
reduced spouse's pension.
