<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow trims losses in face of
jobs data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks trimmed their losses yesterday afternoon even though bonds had
broken into full retreat in the face of strong employment data, writes Frank
McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 26.47 lower at 3,669.50, after
battling back from a 54-point deficit in the final hour of trading. The more
broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was down 3.56 at 447.82, as declining
NYSE issues swamped advances, 1,685 to 546. In the secondary markets, the
American SE composite was off 1.97 at 439.73, and the Nasdaq dropped 7.64 to
732.91.
Keenly awaited data on April employment conditions proved to be a big
letdown for investors who were hoping for a signal that the Federal Reserve
would soon bring to an end a series of interest rate increases which began
three months ago. An hour before the session began, the Commerce Department
announced that US non-farm employers took on 267,000 more workers last
month, against forecasts of about 160,000.
Analysts said the sharp rise suggested an intensification of inflationary
pressures and raised the likelihood that the Fed would now move more
aggressively to slow the economy. Many were convinced the central bank would
soon boost the Federal Funds and discount rates by 50 basis points each.
At the opening the blue chips dropped nearly 35 points, but recovered to
trade about 20 points down within the first hour. Such resilience was
encouraging in view of the rout taking place in the bond market.
But near midday, it became apparent that the Fed would hold off until Monday
at the earliest. Its restraint blackened the already gloomy mood by
suggesting the central bank may not act decisively enough to quell
inflationary expectations. As a result, bond prices dropped further. Late in
the session, the price of benchmark 30-year security was down more than 2
points, with the yield jumping to 7.53 per cent, its highest level in 18
months.
With the Treasury market extending its losses, stocks began sliding for a
second time before touching bottom an hour before the close.
Stocks sensitive to economic trends were among the weakest. Caterpillar
closed down Dollars 4 3/8 to Dollars 108 1/8 , Deere lost Dollars 3 to
Dollars 72 7/8 and International Paper Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 62 7/8 .
Sears was down Dollars 1 1/8 at Dollars 47 1/2 and McDonald's shed Dollars 1
1/8 to Dollars 57 3/4 .
Oil stocks, rising alongside crude prices, offset some of the losses. Arco,
up Dollars 4 5/8 at Dollars 104, was given an extra boost by an upgrading by
Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette. Mobil gained Dollars 2 5/8 to Dollars 79 1/2
and Amoco Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 56 3/4 .
On the Nasdaq, Ben &amp; Jerry's, the Vermont ice cream maker, dropped Dollars 1
1/4 to Dollars 15 1/8 after reporting that frigid winter weather had held
its first-quarter earnings to 13 cents a share, after 21 cents a year
earlier.
Canada
Toronto stocks closed slightly lower in busy activity inflated by hectic
trading of PWA Corporation shares.
Almost all sectors were off, except for the precious metals group, up 5.5
per cent, higher on stronger gold prices. The TSE 300 composite index fell
5.75 to close at 4,254.06 in volume of 97.68m shares valued at CDollars
638.6m. The index dropped about 13 points on the week.
About 38.5m PWA shares were traded and the corporation, in the midst of a
restructuring, closed up 0.02 at 0.58.
Brazil
Brazil stock prices recovered from sharp losses to end up 4.3 per cent in a
highly volatile market that traders said will probably continue as the
October 3 presidential elections approach.
The Bovespa index ended at 15,103 points, up 624 on the day.
</TEXT>
