<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 94 / Letters to the Editor: Resources must not be wasted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Ms HEDDA BIRD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, We hear that fewer women than ever are numbered among senior British
managers.
Recently, while awaiting a delayed flight from Edinburgh to Heathrow, I sat
near the telephones in the Shuttle lounge. Over the next two hours a stream
of businessmen phoned their wives/secretaries/girlfriends to rearrange what
time they were to be collected, postpone dinner appointments, and 'be taken
straight to the opera house'. One man spoke to his child. A similar
procession of businesswomen phoned their nannies/childminders and mothers to
re-arrange children's tea, bath and bedtime. Most of the women talked to the
children, explained why they were going to be late and offered reassurance
and comfort.
This is hardly a random sample but on reflection I pity the men - no wonder
we women start our own businesses.
Hedda Bird,
managing director,
Conservation Papers,
228 London Road, Reading
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
