FT  07 MAY 94 / Miners given pay-off ultimatum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Coal yesterday presented its 10,000 miners with an ultimatum to
accept a new deal on working conditions and redundancy arrangements within
the next two weeks or risk losing a Pounds 6,000 sweetener.
The lump sum is for agreeing to flexible con-ditions including weekend work
and extending the maximum rostered shift from 7 1/2 to 12 hours.
Miners must accept the deal by May 20 or lose the offer, leaving them with
maximum redundancy payouts of Pounds 6,150, British Coal said yesterday.
Mr Kevan Hunt, British Coal's employee relations director said: 'Everyone
must understand this is not only the best offer in town, it's the only
offer.'
The Union of Democratic Mineworkers opposes the offer but the British
Association of Colliery Management has accepted it. Nacods, the pit deputies
union, is considering its response. British Coal said talks are planned at
local level at non-UDM pits.
