<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 94 / Major to fight any challenge to his leadership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major confronted head-on yesterday the growing threat to his
leadership as a shell-shocked Conservative party digested its worst
performance for more than 50 years in a nationwide election.
Confirmation of the government's rout in Thursday's local elections
intensified speculation at Westminster that a similar defeat in the June 9
European elections would spell the end of his premiership.
Mr Paddy Ashdown's Liberal Democrats celebrated the biggest gains in the
battle for 5,000 council seats contested across the country, adding 388 to
their previous total and claiming the party was now winning positive, rather
than protest, votes.
But Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, said his party's strong showing in
once-Tory strongholds around London confirmed it was now poised to win the
next general election. The government held its flagship Wandsworth and
Westminster councils, but Labour now controls 17 of the capital's 32
boroughs against the Conservatives' four. Defeated in such bastions as
Tunbridge Wells, Basildon and Woking, the Conservatives had nationwide
losses of 429 seats.
The result in Scotland was still more damaging. The Conservatives were
driven into fourth place behind Labour, the Scottish National party and the
Liberal Democrats.
As the final results indicated the Tory share of the overall vote had
slumped to 27 per cent - the same as the Liberal Democrats - Mr John
Carlisle, a maverick Tory MP, said he was ready to stand in an autumn
leadership contest.
Other rightwing Conservatives said they had already collected the necessary
34 pledges from backbench colleagues to trigger such a contest.
But in a blunt warning that he would not be driven from office by opponents
in his own party, Mr Major said he would fight off any challenge. Speaking
outside 10 Downing Street before joining the Queen for the formal opening of
the Channel tunnel, he dismissed Mr Carlisle's threat.
The prime minister pledged a Conservative fightback in the poll for the
European Parliament and Mr Major predicted a backlash against his party's
dissidents during the campaign. It would not forgive 'anyone who stands on
the sidelines or utters a discordant note'.
Asked how he would respond to any challenge Mr Major responded briskly: 'If
anybody chooses to engage in that fight, they will find me standing there
waiting for them.' He added: 'I will meet a challenge whenever it comes.'
Cabinet colleagues sought to shore up the prime minister's position with
pledges to unite around the the Tory manifesto for the June 9 election.
Mr Michael Portillo, the rightwing Treasury minister at the centre of a
cabinet row this week over Europe, insisted there was no question of a drive
to oust Mr Major. Mr Michael Heseltine, regarded as the most likely
successor if Mr Major fell, also urged an end to leadership speculation.
