<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 94 / UK Local Elections: Opposition parties vie for top battle
honours - Lib Dems see biggest net gain of seats / Labour does well in
London and holds firm in regions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and ROLAND ADBURGHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Both of the main opposition parties were entitled to wear a broad smile last
night in the aftermath of a result universally seen as a disaster for the
Conservatives.
The Liberal Democrats made by far the biggest number of net gains on the
night - more than 300.
But Labour did well in London - the key area for the party in terms of
demonstrating its ability to win the prize that really matters: the next
general election in 1996 or 1997.
Labour will also have been buoyed by the remarkable extent to which its
share of the vote outside London held up in comparison with the
exceptionally high level of 43.8 per cent the party attained in 1990.
All of this will have given chastened Conservative strategists plenty to
think about. But the most immediate concern to Tories will be the
unexpectedly strong Liberal Democrat showing - particularly in southern
England.
This augurs badly for the next electoral hurdle that the Conservatives must
somehow try to stumble across - June's elections to the European parliament
which will have a significant bearing on Mr John Major's prospects of
remaining party leader.
In this contest, the Liberal Democrats have high hopes of winning a swathe
of Tory-held seats in the south-west and central southern England. Last
night's results will have done nothing to dent their confidence - in spite
of the fact that relatively few councils in south-west England held
elections.
Where elections were held in the region - such as in Mr Chris Patten's
former parliamentary constituency of Bath - the Liberal Democrats performed
outstandingly.
While the Liberal Democrats had hoped to win control of the ancient city -
which they had never previously controlled - their success surpassed all
their expectations. They took seven seats from the Conservatives -
previously the largest party - but also all five seats being defended by
Labour, which now has an insignificant presence on the council.
For Labour, Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, said that
last night's message was that Mr Major was presiding over a government that
was 'even more unpopular' than that of the Thatcher administration at the
height of the poll tax debacle.
'It looks as if outside London we are going to maintain our best result
ever,' he added. The country was sending the Tories a message that they
'have had enough'.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, Labour's deputy leader, focused on the party's success
in holding Birmingham, a prime Conservative target.
'The Tories told us to judge tonight's elections by whether or not they took
control of Birmingham,' she said. 'By those standards alone, tonight has
been a failure for the Tories.'
For the Liberal Democrats, Mr Charles Kennedy, the party president,
characterised the result as 'a big thumbs-up' for the party.
'This proves we have established our position as a national party, retaining
and winning control of councils and becoming the main challengers both to
the Conservatives and Labour in their heartlands,' he said.
Mr Archy Kirkwood, the Liberal Democrat chief whip, said that his party had
'replaced the Tories as the second party in local government'.
Last night, both main opposition parties could be forgiven their
self-congratulation.
If in the European elections the Liberal Democrats inflict a further mauling
on the Conservatives in their south-west English heartlands, they will seem
to be making the running.
But if Labour can resist the temptation to put the Liberal Democrats in its
sights, it may ultimately win the larger prize.
</TEXT>
