<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 94 / CBI warns on pension reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Confederation of British Industry has warned that employers may abandon
salary schemes that link benefits to leaving salaries if the government
insists on implementing some of the main safeguards for occupational
pensions.
Mr Robbie Gilbert, director of employment affairs at the CBI, yesterday told
a pensions seminar that rules recommended by the Goode committee on
occupational pension law reform would raise costs significantly for
employers. He complained specifically of requirements for minimum member
representation on boards of trustees, an industry-funded compensation scheme
and most importantly, minimum solvency standards for schemes.
However, Mr Gilbert conceded that only 20 per cent of chief executives
surveyed by the CBI said they intended to switch to money purchase from
final-salary schemes if they 'looked likely to fall foul of a minimum
solvency standard'.
In money purchase schemes employers and employees contribute a set amount by
contractual arrangement and all funds are deemed to belong to the employee.
About 33 per cent of executives surveyed would increase scheme funding while
another 33 per cent said they would alter their investment strategy.
Because UK pension schemes invest an average of 80 per cent of assets in
equities,the introduction of a minimum solvency standard might prompt some
schemes to shift investment into lower-yielding gilts, increasing funding
costs.
</TEXT>
