<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 94 / Russians taken for Dollars 5m ride: John Mason describes how
three businessmen, who were found guilty yesterday, set up a car fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Three British businessmen were convicted yesterday of a multi-million dollar
fraud on a Russian automotive company which was trying to set up a
large-scale kit car assembly operation after the collapse of the Soviet
command economy.
The fraud, centred on the non-delivery of goods paid for in advance by the
Russian Autokam company, is seen by UK police and prosecutors as a prime
example of the vulnerability of emerging eastern bloc entrepreneurs to
outside exploitation.
At Portsmouth Crown Court Mr Alexander Mullins, a commodity broker, from
Chandler's Ford, Hampshire; Mr Malcolm Jennings, a motor dealer from
Bethersden, Kent; and Mr Charles Johnson, from Brentford, west London, were
all convicted of conspiring to defraud Autokam.
Mr Mullins was also convicted on five charges of stealing almost Dollars 5m
from the company. All three will be sentenced on May 27.
In 1990, Autokam, based 100 miles outside Moscow, was seeking to break into
the automotive market by assembling cars from parts imported from the west.
With strong political backing from the then Gorbachev-led government, the
company planned to build a large plant employing 740 people and using
western production techniques.
It intended importing parts from an established western manufacturer and
assembling them into complete vehicles. The bulk of the cars would then be
exported back to the west to earn hard currency.
Its directors had experience in tank and truck manufacture under the old
Soviet regime but little experience of operating in a market economy.
They also lacked the support previously offered by the Soviet state.
The Autokam directors also demonstrated considerable trust that a British
businessman's word was always his bond. This proved to be sadly misplaced.
Autokam's plans had begun to falter when their negotiations with western
manufacturers such as BMW foundered. The company's lack of production
experience meant no deal could be agreed.
Instead, in summer 1990, it turned to Mr Mullins, who was looking for
business opportunities in the emerging Russian market economy. He persuaded
Autokam to agree to purchase the parts for 1,000 kit cars for Dollars 5m.
The design of these cars had been carried out by the respected
Hampshire-based Rickman Brothers motor engineers. However, their cars were
hardly high-quality concepts. Their design involved grafting a glass-fibre
body on to a steel chassis with the engine and other mechanical parts
coming, second-hand, from obsolete Ford Escorts.
The Rickmans doubted the suitability of their car for such an enterprise but
Mr Mullins insisted the project was viable and bought their factory. He then
agreed a second contract with Autokam - to supply 100,000 car kits at a
price of Dollars 5,000 each.
Mr Mullins was the main perpetrator of the fraud. He was supported by Mr
Jennings, who became his technical adviser, and Mr Johnson, who was brought
in to provide financial advice.
The Russians paid the Dollars 5m for the first contract but their concerns
mounted. To allay these fears, the three men used a variety of fraudulent
devices, such as false accountancy reports and warranties, to persuade the
Russians they were complying with the contract.
All the Russians received for their Dollars 5m were 47 vehicles containing
second hand parts, such as wiring looms, bought from Belgian scrapyards and
passed off as new.
Increasingly suspicious, the Russians contacted a British solicitor who
contacted the police. The police handed the case over to the Serious Fraud
Office.
The experience left Autokam directors chastened, but not deterred, according
to the company's UK solicitor Mr Andrew Stacey. 'They lacked commercial
experience and perhaps had too much trust in those they were dealing with.
They have now learnt some valuable lessons,' he said.
In spite of the fraud, the company now assembles cars from parts
manufactured by Ford and has taken a substantial interest in Reliant, the
British motor manufacturer.
</TEXT>
<XX>
