<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 94 / World Commodities Prices: Wool
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Prices paid at wool auctions this week increased steadily, and with
offerings declining in the closing stages of the selling season it became
more difficult to imagine a setback. The Australian market indicator reached
587c/kg on May 5, a new peak for the season. Nervousness about stockpile
offering to be offered by fixed schedule from July dissipated some time ago
and the market is inclined now to assess this as a potentially strengthening
rather than a weakening factor. The wool using industry is keeping busy but
there is eagerness to see new business coming through at the higher prices
now being paid for wool. After a long quiet period it is hoped that the
latest dearer price trend is finally bringing out more buying interest.
Currency volatility affecting the US and Australian dollars has disturbed
price calculations during the past week.
