<HEADLINE>
FT  06 MAY 94 / International Company News: NYSE approves policy to protect
shareholders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The New York Stock Exchange has approved a new shareholder voting rights
policy that will prevent US companies from restricting or diluting the
voting powers of shareholders through special stock issues.
Mr James Buck, the NYSE's corporate secretary, said: 'The new policy
prohibits the most abusive types of recapitalisations which take away the
voting rights of shareholders.'
Under the policy, companies will not be able to conduct share exchange
offers where the stock issued carries lesser voting rights than of the stock
originally owned by shareholders. They will be prohibited from adopting
plans which require shareholders to hold stock a certain length of time
before they can use the stock to vote, and from issuing 'super-voting' stock
above existing common stock, unless such stock existed at the time of the
original flotation.
However, companies with existing dual-class capital structures will not be
affected by the new policy.
The NYSE's new policy has been approved by the American Stock Exchange and
the National Association of Securities Dealers. The rules should be quickly
approved by the Securities and Exchange Commission. Last year, Mr Arthur
Levitt, SEC chairman, proposed the exchanges adopt a uniform policy to
protecting shareholders' voting rights.
The exchanges were able to draw up a new voting rights policy after reaching
agreement with the Business Roundtable, which represents the chief
executives of the largest US public companies. In 1990, the Roundtable
successfully appealed to a Federal court to block the SEC introducing a
voting rights policy. Since then its position has softened and, according to
Mr Buck of the NYSE, the new policy enjoyed 'the overwhelming support of the
business community'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
